56","1510":"1510","1532":"1532","1476":"1476","1553":"1553","1541":"1541","1573":"1573","Stamford, South Kesteven District, Lincolnshire, England":"Stamford, Lincolnshire, England","Witham on the Hill, Lincolnshire, England":"Witham on the Hill, Lincolnshire, England","Stamford, Lincoln, England":"Stamford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Swanhall, Suffolk, England":"Swans Hall, Suffolk, England","Stamford, Lincolnshire, England":"Stamford, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Dycons was born in 1476, in Stamford, Lincolnshire, England, her father, Sir John L DICONS, was 29 and her mother, Lady Margaret SEMARK, was 25. She married Sir David Cecil, High Sheriff of Northamptonshire in 1489, in Stamford, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1532, in Stamford, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 56, and was buried in Stamford, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"1476–1532":"1476–1532","1456–1541":"1456–1541","1492–1536":"1492–1536","1495–1553":"1495–1553","1510–1573